      "side": 1,
      "message": "I didn\u0027t notice this the first time, but if both sides have a value, we actually aren\u0027t supposed to destroy the object and re-construct; we need to do `fPayload.fValue \u003d other.fPayload.fValue`. Assigning a value into an object is sometimes more efficient than destroying it entirely and reconstructing it from scratch (or could technically even do something totally different). e.g. assigning a vector into another vector could allow it to reuse its storage instead of freeing it and reallocating it.\n\nThere are really four possible combinations and each one behaves a little differently:\n\n  empty-value \u003d empty-value;   // both empty, nothing called\n  has-value \u003d empty-value;     // both empty, ~value called\n  empty-value \u003d has-value;     // both have value, value::copy-ctor called\n  has-value \u003d has-other-value; // both have other-value, value::operator\u003d called",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 60,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 64,
        "endChar": 13
      },
      "revId": "3587de3094cc6d09b9aae8d97c1011c50b14735d",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
